SIMPLE: hyena
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hyena
<hw>Hy*e"na</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Hyenas</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L. <ets>hyaena</ets>, Gr.
<?/, orig., a sow, but usually, a Libyan wild beast, prob., the hyena,
fr. <?/ hog: cf. F. <ets>hy⟦egrave⟧ne</ets>. See <er>Sow</er> female
hog.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any carnivorous mammal of the family
<fam>Hy⟦ae⟧nid⟦ae⟧</fam>, doglike nocturnal mammals of Africa and
southern Asia, of which three living species are known. They are large
and strong, but cowardly. They feed chiefly on carrion, and are
nocturnal in their habits.</def> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>hy⟦ae⟧na</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> hyaena.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The striped hyena (<spn>Hy⟦ae⟧na striata</spn>) inhabits
Southern Asia and a large part of Africa. The brown hyena (<spn>Hy⟦ae⟧na
brunnea</spn>), and the spotted hyena (<spn>Crocuta maculata</spn>), are
found in Southern Africa. The extinct cave hyena (<spn>Hy⟦ae⟧na
spel⟦ae⟧a</spn>) inhabited England and France.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Cave hyena</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Cave</er>.</cd>
-- <col><b>Hyena dog</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a South African
canine animal (<spn>Lycaon venaticus</spn>), which hunts in packs,
chiefly at night. It is smaller than the common wolf, with very large,
erect ears, and a bushy tail. Its color is reddish or yellowish brown,
blotched with black and white. Called also <altname>hunting
dog</altname>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

